I walked across 
the woodyard, and breathed 
the blue fumes the chainsaw 
belched, listening 
to the pinging wind bells, 
thinking of the twelve years 
of wanting, apart 
and together. We’ve 
kissed all weekend; 
we want to drive the hundred 
miles and try it 
again. She wants a house 
full of cups and the ghosts 
of last century’s 
lesbians; I want 
a clean gas flame. She wants 
a woodstove, three cords 
of ash, an axe; 
I want a spotless 
apartment, a fast 
